# üü¢ PRE-WEEK: I/O (INPUT/OUTPUT) - ESSENTIAL BASICS

## Learning Outcomes
By the end of this section, you will:
‚úÖ Understand what I/O means  
‚úÖ Take input from user (keyboard)  
‚úÖ Display output (screen)  
‚úÖ Use I/O in C, C++, JavaScript  



## What is I/O?

**I/O = Input + Output**

```
INPUT:  Data entering the program (from user's keyboard)
OUTPUT: Data leaving the program (to user's screen)

FLOW:
User types ‚Üí Program reads (INPUT)
Program processes ‚Üí Program displays (OUTPUT)
```

---

## I/O in C

**Header Required:**
```c
#include <stdio.h>  // Standard Input/Output
```

**Output - printf():**
```c
printf("Hello, World!");          // Print text
printf("Number: %d\n", 42);       // Print integer
printf("Name: %s\n", "Amit");     // Print string
```

**Input - scanf():**
```c
int age;
scanf("%d", &age);  // Read integer
printf("You are %d years old\n", age);
```

**Complete I/O Example (C):**
```c
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int age;
    
    printf("Enter your age: ");
    scanf("%d", &age);
    
    printf("You are %d years old\n", age);
    
    return 0;
}
```

**Output (if user enters 25):**
```
Enter your age: 25
You are 25 years old
```

---

## I/O in C++

**Header Required:**
```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
```

**Output - cout:**
```cpp
cout << "Hello, World!";
cout << "Number: " << 42 << endl;
```

**Input - cin:**
```cpp
int age;
cin >> age;  // Read integer
cout << "You are " << age << " years old" << endl;
```

**Complete I/O Example (C++):**
```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int age;
    
    cout << "Enter your age: ";
    cin >> age;
    
    cout << "You are " << age << " years old" << endl;
    
    return 0;
}
```

**Output (if user enters 25):**
```
Enter your age: 25
You are 25 years old
```

---

## I/O in JavaScript

**Output Methods:**
```javascript
console.log("Hello, World!");     // Browser console
alert("Hello!");                  // Popup box
document.write("Text");           // Write to page
```

**Input Method:**
```javascript
let age = prompt("Enter your age:");  // Popup input
```

**Complete I/O Example (JavaScript):**
```javascript
let age = prompt("Enter your age:");
alert("You are " + age + " years old");
console.log("Age: " + age);
```

**Output (if user enters 25):**
```
Alert popup: "You are 25 years old"
Console: Age: 25
```

---

## Multiple Inputs/Outputs (C++)

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    string name;
    int age;
    float salary;
    
    cout << "Enter name: ";
    cin >> name;
    
    cout << "Enter age: ";
    cin >> age;
    
    cout << "Enter salary: ";
    cin >> salary;
    
    cout << "\n--- Your Details ---\n";
    cout << "Name: " << name << endl;
    cout << "Age: " << age << endl;
    cout << "Salary: " << salary << endl;
    
    return 0;
}
```

**Output (if user enters Raj, 25, 50000):**
```
Enter name: Raj
Enter age: 25
Enter salary: 50000

--- Your Details ---
Name: Raj
Age: 25
Salary: 50000
```

---

## üìö In-Depth Theory: I/O Operations

### Understanding printf() in C

The `printf()` function is used to display formatted output on the screen. It is part of the standard I/O library (`stdio.h`).

**General Form:**
```c
printf("<format string>", <list of variables>);
```

**Format Specifiers:**
- `%d` - for printing integer values
- `%f` - for printing real (float) values  
- `%c` - for printing character values
- `%s` - for printing string values
- `\n` - newline character (moves cursor to next line)

**Key Points:**
- The format string can contain both format specifiers and regular text
- Format specifiers are replaced by actual values from the variable list
- Multiple values can be printed in one `printf()` statement
- `printf()` can also print the result of expressions directly

**Example:**
```c
printf("%d %d %f %f", p, n, r, si);
printf("Simple interest = Rs. %f", si);
printf("Prin = %d \nRate = %f", p, r);
```

### Understanding scanf() in C

The `scanf()` function is used to read formatted input from the keyboard.

**General Form:**
```c
scanf("<format string>", &variable);
```

**Critical Rule:** Always use `&` (address-of operator) before variable names in `scanf()`, except for strings.

**Why `&` is needed:** `scanf()` needs the memory address where the input value should be stored. The `&` operator provides this address.

**Common Format Specifiers:**
- `%d` - for reading integers
- `%f` - for reading float values
- `%c` - for reading single character
- `%s` - for reading strings (no `&` needed for string arrays)

**Example:**
```c
int age;
float salary;
char grade;
char name[50];

scanf("%d", &age);        // Note: & before age
scanf("%f", &salary);     // Note: & before salary
scanf("%c", &grade);      // Note: & before grade
scanf("%s", name);        // Note: NO & for string array
```

### Understanding cin and cout in C++

**cout (Console Output):**
- `cout` is an object of the `ostream` class
- Uses the insertion operator `<<` to send data to the output stream
- `endl` is used to insert a newline and flush the output buffer
- Multiple values can be chained using multiple `<<` operators

**cin (Console Input):**
- `cin` is an object of the `istream` class  
- Uses the extraction operator `>>` to read data from the input stream
- Automatically handles type conversion
- Multiple values can be read in sequence

**Key Differences from C:**
- No format specifiers needed (type-safe)
- No `&` operator needed (automatic reference handling)
- More intuitive and less error-prone
- Requires `#include <iostream>` and `using namespace std;`

**Example:**
```cpp
int age;
float salary;
string name;

cout << "Enter age: ";
cin >> age;                    // No & needed

cout << "Enter salary: ";
cin >> salary;                 // No & needed

cout << "Enter name: ";
cin >> name;                   // No & needed

cout << "Age: " << age << endl;
cout << "Salary: " << salary << endl;
```

### Understanding JavaScript I/O

**Output Methods:**

1. **console.log()** - Most common method
   - Outputs to browser console (F12 Developer Tools)
   - Can print multiple values separated by commas
   - Automatically converts values to strings

2. **alert()** - Popup dialog
   - Blocks execution until user clicks OK
   - Useful for simple notifications
   - Not recommended for production code

3. **document.write()** - Writes to HTML page
   - Overwrites entire page if called after page load
   - Generally avoided in modern JavaScript

**Input Methods:**

1. **prompt()** - Popup input dialog
   - Returns string value (needs conversion for numbers)
   - Returns `null` if user cancels
   - Blocks execution until user responds

2. **HTML Input Elements** - Modern approach
   - Use `<input>` elements in HTML
   - Access values via DOM: `document.getElementById('id').value`

**Type Conversion in JavaScript:**
```javascript
let age = prompt("Enter age:");  // Returns string "25"
age = parseInt(age);              // Convert to integer: 25
// OR
age = Number(age);                // Convert to number: 25
// OR
age = +age;                       // Unary + converts to number: 25
```

### Memory and I/O Operations

**How I/O Works Internally:**

1. **Input Process:**
   - User types data on keyboard
   - Data stored in input buffer
   - Program reads from buffer using `scanf()`, `cin`, or `prompt()`
   - Data converted to appropriate data type
   - Stored in program variable

2. **Output Process:**
   - Program prepares data in memory
   - Data formatted according to format specifiers (C) or automatically (C++/JS)
   - Sent to output buffer
   - Displayed on screen/console

**Buffer Concept:**
- Input/output buffers are temporary storage areas
- Buffering improves efficiency by reducing system calls
- `endl` in C++ flushes the buffer immediately
- `\n` in C/C++ also flushes buffer in most cases

---

## Common Mistakes (I/O)

| Mistake | Why Wrong | Correct |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| `scanf("%d", age);` | Missing & operator | `scanf("%d", &age);` |
| `cin >> "name"` | Wrong syntax - using string literal instead of variable | `cin >> name;` |
| `printf("%d", 3.14);` | Type mismatch - using %d for float | `printf("%f", 3.14);` |
| No `#include <stdio.h>` | scanf/printf functions won't work without header | Add `#include <stdio.h>` at top |
| `scanf("%s", &name);` | String arrays don't need & operator | `scanf("%s", name);` |
| Using `var` instead of `let/const` | Outdated, function scope issues | Use `let` or `const` |

---

